```java
this.yieldLimit = waitStrategy.isYield() ? spinLimit / 2 : 0;
this.block = waitStrategy.isBlock();
```

For `BUSY_SPIN`, `isYield() = false`, `isBlock() = false`. So `yieldLimit = 0`, `block = false`.

For `YIELD`, `isYield() = true`, `isBlock() = false`. So `yieldLimit = spinLimit / 2`. This means after `spinLimit/2` iterations, it starts yielding.

If we change the throughput tests to use `YIELD` wait strategy instead of `BUSY_SPIN`, the consumers will yield instead of hard-spinning when waiting. This would drastically reduce `getMinimumSequence` CPU time. But it might increase latency because yielding means context switching.

However, in the throughput benchmark, the consumers are mostly NOT waiting - they're processing events. They only wait at group boundaries. Yielding at group boundaries is probably fine and would save a lot of CPU.

